sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K648016
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Fast-Fusion GFP-Xyle Reporter (TEV cleaveage with long linker)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This is a fast-acting reporter using the Xyle gene (BBa_K648011) fused to GFP. In its normal un-cleaved state the polymerization ability necessary for enzymatic action is inactivated. Once the fusion protein is cleaved by the TEV protease the catechol-2,3-dioxygenase enzyme encoded by the Xyle gene is able to convert catechol to the bright yellow product 2-hydroxy-cis,cis-muconic semialdehyde. This reporter is able to produce a visible color response in a matter of minutes.
This version uses the TEV cleavage site (BBa_K648008) followed by the largest of the three flexible fusion protein linkers (BBa_K648006). The linker is attached to the N-terminus of the Xyle gene.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jim Rose
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The design of this part was inspired by the Imperial College London 2010 iGEM Team's Fast-Response module, part BBa_K316007.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: All parts were assembled via standard 25 assembly methods.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K648013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the standard GFP protein reporter (E0040) cloned with the prefix/suffix required for standard 25 assembly. It can easily be used to create fusion proteins through this method.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jim Rose
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part is similar to the part BBa_E0040 commonly used as a reporter.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:

Forward (56.88 degrees) TATTGAATTCGCGGCCGCTTCTAGATGGCCGGCCGTAAAGGAGAAGAACTTTTC
Reverse (56.95 degrees) AATACTGCAGCGGCCGCTACTAGTATTAACCGGTCTTGTCGTCATCATCTTTATAAT

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K648008
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: TEV protease cleaveage site with Standard 25 Prefix/Suffix
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the cleaveage site for th Tobacco etch virus(TEV) protease commonly used for cleaving fusion proteins. It encodes for the amino acids E N L Y F Q G which are cleaved by the TEV protease. This part also contains the prefix/suffix required for standard 25 assembly into fusion parts.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K648006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Long 10AA Fusion Protein Linker with Standard 25 Prefix/Suffix
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the longest of the three fusion protein linkers created by the Penn State 2011 iGEM team. It encodes for the ten amino acids GENLYFQSGG and has a prefix and suffix compatible with assembly standard 25. It is used in one of the variants of our Fast-Fusion protein reporter system.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K648011
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This is a mutated version of the Xyle reporter gene which encodes for the enzyme catechol-2,3-dioxygenase (metapyrocatechase), which converts catechol to the bright yellow product 2-hydroxy-cis,cis-muconic semialdehyde. This version of Xyle has been made compatible with standard 25 assembly methods by removing three restriction sites (two NgoMIV sites: at bp 315 and 486, as well as one AgeI site: at bp 837). These mutations were made synonymous with the original sequence and codon optimized for E. Coli.
Because of the synonymous mutations, this gene can be easily used to create fusion protein parts. For more information on the Xyle gene and its uses as a reporter see part BBa_J33204.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jim Rose
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The original genetic material for this part came from part BBa_K316007 which was mutated via PCR based site-directed mutagensis. The xyle portion of this large part was then amplified via PCR reaction and cloned into a new vector along with a prefix/suffix for standard 25 assembly.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The mutations in this gene were made so that they were synonymous and codon optimized for E. coli cells. The part also contains the prefix/suffix for standard 25 assembly with addition restriction sites NgoMIV and AgeI.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
